Problem domain¶

[go back to the top]

Introduction¶

At MoneyLion we are constantly working to assess the risk of our applicants more accurately. Being successful in this objective enables us to better price customers and mitigate losses on our portfolio of loans. The following challenge asks you to work with a dataset of loan repayment. It is intentionally meant to be open-ended. The point is not to arrive at a predetermined answer or search for the lowest possible standard error. Rather, the hope is that it will force you to ask relevant questions about the data, do some preliminary exploration, perform the necessary manipulations or aggregations, generate visualizations, and reach conclusions or insights.

Data¶

You are provided with 3 files: loan.csv, payment.csv, and clarity_underwriting_variables.csv. The files are comma-separated, with the column names in the first row. The detailed description of each column is available in the MoneyLion Data Scientist Assessment Data Dictionary document. This can be found in the dictionaries.zip file.

Guildelines¶

In this assessment, we do not expect a model built (feel free to attempt if you want to), but we want to see a proposal or plan around how you would approach the problem of predicting loan risk or quality (loan repayment) on a given loan application. Before diving into developing a plan, start with some exploratory data analysis (EDA). Take a look at some distributions of some of the variates. Think about how would you define a loan as risky. How would you select your sample if you were to build this model? Back your proposal with some EDA and insights you discovered from the data.

Understand the problem¶

[go back to the top]

From the problem domain, the objective is to access the risk of applicants more accurately. With this objective, it is allowed but not limited to perform:

  • Data preparation
  • Data exploration
  • Data visualization
  • Model building

From the correlation map above, paymentAmount is highly correlated with principal and fees columns (As payment amount usually equals to fees + principal).

Based on some basic exploration, I will extract loanId, paymentAmount and paymentStatus columns from this dataset.

  • loanId - To merge with other datasets
  • paymentAmount - Sum up total payment amount by each loan (loanId) if paymentStatus = Checked. This is the effective amount paid for each loanId
  • paymentStatus - Sum up total count of different payment status for each loanId

From the graph above and the definition of the loan status, it's easier to determine a loan is risky or not.

Risky Loan Status
0 Loan Paid Off,New Loan,Pending Paid Off,Returned Item
1 Charged Off,Charged Off Paid Off,External Collection,Internal Collection,Settled Bankruptcy

I didn't include Customer Voided New Loan and Withdrawn Application as it's hard to define them as risky or non-risky (There's a lot of reason that leads to both categories).

Next, I will perform feature creation. Looking at the dataset information above, anon_ssn which is the client ssn is not what I interested about. In fact, I'm more curious about how many loans one client is holding. Therefore, I will create new column called nLoanPerSSN to calculate that. Besides, it may also useful to know number of paid off loan by one client. As a result, I will create another column nPaidOffPerSSN to calculate this.

Name Transformers Columns
ohe OneHotEncoder ohe_features
binary_ohe OneHotEncoder binary_ohe_features
odn OrdinalEncoder odn_features
lbl OneHotEncoder lbl_features
scaler StandardScaler scaler_features
  • OneHotEncoder: Creates a list of columns based on number of category and assigns a value of 1 if the sample is belongs to that category
  • OrdinalEncoder: Converts each sample into integer values and the encoded data represents the sequence of labels
  • StandardScaler: Normalized the data using formula $Z = \frac{X-\mu}{\sigma}$

[go back to the top]


Alright, now I've all done for the data preprocessing. It's time to feed the data into the model. I will use four different models for training.


    

  1. Logistic Regression
    2. 

  2. Decision Tree
    3. 

  3. Random Forest
    4. 

  4. Voting
    5. 



For the performance evaluation, it is important to accurately predict that the loan is risky (precision) at the same time detect as many risky loans as possible (recall). Therefore, I will use $f_{1}$ score as evaluation metric as I'm predicting whether the loan is risky or not. Here's are several reasons:


    

  • $f_{1}$ score is combination of precision and recall into a single metric
    • 

  • Harmonic mean of precision and recall
    • 

  • Gives much more weight to low values
    • 

  • Produces high score only if both precision and recall and high
    •

# model training and evaluation
df_score = pd.DataFrame(columns=['model', 'train_accuracy','valid_accuracy', 'accuracy_difference', 'f1_score','precision','recall'])

pipelines = [log_pipeline, dec_pipeline, rand_pipeline]
names = ['Logistic Regression', 'Decision Tree', 'Random Forest']

i = 0
for pipeline in pipelines:
#   train model
    pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
#   get score
    train_score = pipeline.score(X_train, y_train)
    valid_score = pipeline.score(X_valid, y_valid)
    y_pred = pipeline.predict(X_valid)
    f1 = f1_score(y_valid, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_valid, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_valid, y_pred)
    
    dict = {
        'model': names[i],
        'train_accuracy': train_score,
        'valid_accuracy': valid_score,
        'accuracy_difference': train_score - valid_score,
        'f1_score': f1,
        'precision': precision,
        'recall': recall
    }
    df_score = df_score.append(dict, ignore_index=True)
    i+=1

df_score.sort_values(by='f1_score', ascending=False)

First, I will get feature importances from XGBClassifier. Then, given a set of thresholds, I will try to drop some features if the importance is less than the specific threshold and determine which model performs the best. Below code is a function to get feature names from the preprocessor after being transform (ColumnTransformer's get_feature_names() fails if at least one transformer does not create new columns) The original code of the function is here.











In [61]:



     


import warnings

def get_feature_names(column_transformer):
    """Get feature names from all transformers.
    Returns
    -------
    feature_names : list of strings
        Names of the features produced by transform.
    """
    # Remove the internal helper function
    #check_is_fitted(column_transformer)
    
    # Turn loopkup into function for better handling with pipeline later
    def get_names(trans):
        # >> Original get_feature_names() method
        if trans == 'drop' or (
                hasattr(column, '__len__') and not len(column)):
            return []
        if trans == 'passthrough':
            if hasattr(column_transformer, '_df_columns'):
                if ((not isinstance(column, slice))
                        and all(isinstance(col, str) for col in column)):
                    return column
                else:
                    return column_transformer._df_columns[column]
            else:
                indices = np.arange(column_transformer._n_features)
                return ['x%d' % i for i in indices[column]]
        if not hasattr(trans, 'get_feature_names'):
        # >>> Change: Return input column names if no method avaiable
            # Turn error into a warning
            warnings.warn("Transformer %s (type %s) does not "
                                 "provide get_feature_names. "
                                 "Will return input column names if available"
                                 % (str(name), type(trans).__name__))
            # For transformers without a get_features_names method, use the input
            # names to the column transformer
            if column is None:
                return []
            else:
                return [name + "__" + f for f in column]

        return [name + "__" + f for f in trans.get_feature_names()]
    
    ### Start of processing
    feature_names = []
    
    # Allow transformers to be pipelines. Pipeline steps are named differently, so preprocessing is needed
    if type(column_transformer) == sklearn.pipeline.Pipeline:
        l_transformers = [(name, trans, None, None) for step, name, trans in column_transformer._iter()]
    else:
        # For column transformers, follow the original method
        l_transformers = list(column_transformer._iter(fitted=True))
    
    
    for name, trans, column, _ in l_transformers: 
        if type(trans) == sklearn.pipeline.Pipeline:
            # Recursive call on pipeline
            _names = get_feature_names(trans)
            # if pipeline has no transformer that returns names
            if len(_names)==0:
                _names = [name + "__" + f for f in column]
            feature_names.extend(_names)
        else:
            feature_names.extend(get_names(trans))
    
    return feature_names

# set of thresholds
thresholds = [0.01, 0.001, 0.0001, 0]

# train the model given the threshold
for threshold in thresholds:
    drop_columns = df_imp.loc[df_imp.feature_importances < threshold, ['index']].values
    drop_columns = [item for sublist in drop_columns for item in sublist]
    preprocessor_2 = ColumnTransformer([("drop", "drop", drop_columns)], remainder='passthrough')
    xgb_pipeline = Pipeline(
    steps=[('preprocessor', preprocessor),
           ('preprocessor_2', preprocessor_2),
           ('xgb_cf', xgb_cf)
          ])
    xgb_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)

    train_score = xgb_pipeline.score(X_train, y_train)
    valid_score = xgb_pipeline.score(X_valid, y_valid)
    y_pred = xgb_pipeline.predict(X_valid)
    f1 = f1_score(y_valid, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_valid, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_valid, y_pred)
    dict = {
        'threshold': threshold,
        'number_of_dropped_columns': len(drop_columns),
        'train_accuracy': train_score,
        'valid_accuracy': valid_score,
        'accuracy_difference': train_score - valid_score,
        'f1_score': f1,
        'precision': precision,
        'recall': recall
    }
    df_score = df_score.append(dict, ignore_index=True)

df_score.sort_values(by='f1_score', ascending=False)

From the table above, threshold 0.001 produces the best result for all metrics (but still a bit of overfitting as training accuracy is 0.05 higher than validation accuracy). So, we will use XGBoost Classifier with 0.001 threshold as our model. For the next step, I will search to find for optimum hyperparameters. In this case, I didn't use GridSearchCV as there will be missing categories if I split the data into KFold (For example one category exists in certain fold but not the other folds as the number of the specific category is too less). Therefore, I code a similar function to GridSearchCV without using KFold.


Reminder: following cell takes about 20 - 30 minutes to execute¶

xgb_cf__eta = [0.01, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3]
xgb_cf__gamma = [0.01, 0.1, 1]
xgb_cf__max_depth = [3, 5, 7, 10]
xgb_cf__min_child_weight = [1, 3, 5]
xgb_cf__subsample = [0.6, 0.8, 1.0]

drop_columns = df_imp.loc[df_imp.feature_importances < 0.001, ['index']].values
drop_columns = [item for sublist in drop_columns for item in sublist]

df_grid = pd.DataFrame(columns=['eta', 'gamma', 'max_depth', 'min_child_weight', 'subsample', 'train_accuracy',
                                 'valid_accuracy', 'accuracy_difference', 'f1_score','precision','recall'])

from time import time

i = 1
for eta in xgb_cf__eta:
    for gamma in xgb_cf__gamma:
        for max_depth in xgb_cf__max_depth:
            for min_child_weight in xgb_cf__min_child_weight:
                for subsample in xgb_cf__subsample:
                    
                    t1 = time()
                    
                    xgb_cf = XGBClassifier(random_state=1, eta=eta, gamma=gamma, max_depth=max_depth, min_child_weight=min_child_weight, subsample=subsample)
                    xgb_pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[('preprocessor', preprocessor), ('preprocessor_2', preprocessor_2), 
                                                   ('xgb_cf', xgb_cf)])
                    xgb_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)
                    
                    train_score = xgb_pipeline.score(X_train, y_train)
                    valid_score = xgb_pipeline.score(X_valid, y_valid)
                    y_pred = xgb_pipeline.predict(X_valid)
                    f1 = f1_score(y_valid, y_pred)
                    precision = precision_score(y_valid, y_pred)
                    recall = recall_score(y_valid, y_pred)
                    
                    dict = {
                        'eta': eta,
                        'gamma': gamma,
                        'max_depth': max_depth,
                        'min_child_weight': min_child_weight,
                        'subsample': subsample,
                        'train_accuracy': train_score,
                        'valid_accuracy': valid_score,
                        'accuracy_difference': train_score - valid_score,
                        'f1_score': f1,
                        'precision': precision,
                        'recall': recall
                    }
                    
                    df_grid = df_grid.append(dict, ignore_index=True)
                    
                    t2 = time()
                    elapsed = t2 - t1
                    print(f'#{i}: Elapsed time is {elapsed:.2f} seconds.')
                    i += 1

Therefore, I will select the model with a high f1_score and came with a small accuracy difference. For model #203, the $f_{1}$ score is 0.906671 which is $\approx 0.0006$ lower than the highest but it comes with a much lower accuracy difference. By considering the trade-off between them, I decide to choose this model as the final model.

Final Notes¶
[go back to the top]


Some final thoughts about the data, model and further improvements











    

  • Feature engineering and data preprocessing are solely based on personal knowledge and assumption including defining a risky loan and this may lead to a highly biased model
    • 

  • More knowledge on finance especially in the context of loan is needed in order to create better features from the dataset
    • 

  • It is hard to find the relationship that differs between risky and non-risky loan as the distribution for both side are similar and this may be the reason of status_rejected scores the highest in the model feature importances and contribute for about $51\%$ as this feature differs the most
    • 

  • Payment status, effective payment amount, first payment status and number of paid off loan are the most important factors to predict risky loan (Refer to feature importances table) but in real world situation, we will not know their payment status, effective payment amount and first payment status if we didn't approve the loan at first. This may be the limitation of the model usage where we can only predict the client that has receive loans before from the company (where their past data are available)
    • 

  • In real world, risky loan consists of only a small portion which is harder to be trained since the class is imbalance and it is needed to collect more data or using up-sampling technique the get a better model result
    • 

  • The model can be tuned towards recall metric as we have to capture more possible risky loans
    •
